; bmf-native-runtime.form — Path C: BMF rule machinery inside the kernel
;
; The trinity scan: (A) scan_run lowered byte-class loops into the kernel;
; (B) .fkb cache moved expensive parse output to Form-side disk; (C) lifts
; the per-token state machine — apply-object-rule + match-object-pattern —
; into the kernel itself. Path D, the next altitude, is a true BMF bytecode
; mode where rule shapes are pre-compiled into a tight instruction stream
; the kernel dispatches without traversing the rule Recipe at all.
;
; The deep claim: every grammar in form-stdlib/grammars/ (python-bmf,
; go-bmf, ts-bmf, rust-bmf, bml, natural-bmf, image/audio/video-bmf) is
; written to the SAME match-object-pattern / apply-object-rule surface
; defined in form-stdlib/engine.fk. Lift that surface into the kernel
; once and every grammar gains native speed from a single feature.

(do
    ;; --- current shape (interpreted) -------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; A BMF rule (form-stdlib/engine.fk:1646-1661) is a Form list:
    ;;
    ;;   (name pattern action [inverse [reverse-emitter]])
    ;;
    ;; Pattern is a tagged-list tree:
    ;;
    ;;   ("object" kind value)              ; literal: match one bmf-object
    ;;   ("sequence" p1 p2 ...)             ; ordered concatenation
    ;;   ("choice"   p1 p2 ...)             ; first-match alternative
    ;;   ("capture"  name child)            ; bind sub-match under name
    ;;   ("star"     child)                 ; zero-or-more
    ;;   ("opt"      child)                 ; zero-or-one
    ;;   ("cut")                            ; commit sentinel
    ;;   ("stop")                           ; explicit failure
    ;;
    ;; A bmf-object is a cell:  ("cell" kind value source inverse).
    ;; An object-stream is a Form list of those cells.
    ;;
    ;; match-object-pattern dispatches by tag and recurses through the
    ;; pattern tree, building up a capture-list (alist of pairs) and
    ;; returning ("match" caps rest) or ("fail" reason) /
    ;; ("fail-cut" reason).
    ;;
    ;; apply-object-rule wraps the result: take the consumed prefix,
    ;; wrap it as bmf-match-source, call the rule's action closure with
    ;; the captures-as-collection, then synthesize the result bmf-object
    ;; with rule-name as its kind and the action's recipe as its value.
    ;;
    ;; End-to-end trace for the simplest rule, drawn from
    ;; tests/bmf-object-runtime.fk:
    ;;
    ;;   rule    = ("start" ("capture" "_1" ("object" "int" "")) emit-int undo)
    ;;   stream  = ( ("cell" "int" "7" ...) )
    ;;
    ;;   apply-object-rule
    ;;     → match-object-pattern  ("capture" "_1" ("object" "int" ""))
    ;;         → match-object-capture
    ;;             → match-object-pattern  ("object" "int" "")
    ;;                 → match-object-literal  ← STATE MACHINE TICK
    ;;             → cap-set "_1" → ("match" ((_1 . 7)) ())
    ;;     → bmf-caps-to-collection         ← Form list rewalk
    ;;     → take consumed prefix           ← Form list rewalk
    ;;     → bmf-match-source captures span ← Form list construction
    ;;     → (rule-action captures)         ← user closure invoked
    ;;     → bmf-object rule-name recipe …  ← cell constructor
    ;;
    ;; Every arrow is a walker dispatch. The state-machine ticks
    ;; (literal matches, sequence steps, choice fallbacks) carry the
    ;; same per-step walker cost as the bytes did before scan_run
    ;; lowered byte-class loops.

    ;; --- where the overhead bites ----------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; Per match-object-pattern call:
    ;;   - 8-way tag dispatch (str_eq cascade)
    ;;   - tag string allocation/comparison
    ;;   - capture-list cons + linear lookup
    ;;   - mk-match / mk-fail list construction
    ;;
    ;; Per literal:
    ;;   - bmf-object-kind walk into cell, str_eq
    ;;   - bmf-object-value walk into cell, str_eq
    ;;   - cap-empty + cons of new caps list
    ;;
    ;; A rule with 10 tokens in its sequence pays ~50 walker dispatches
    ;; per match attempt. Multiply by the number of rules a top-level
    ;; choice tries before one commits, times the number of top-level
    ;; matches across a document. python-bmf scanning a 10K-line file
    ;; runs millions of these dispatches.

    ;; --- the minimal native shape ----------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; Signature (sibling-parity across Go/Rust/TS):
    ;;
    ;;   bmf_apply_rule_native(rule-recipe, object-stream-list)
    ;;       → match-recipe-or-nil
    ;;
    ;; Inputs are already-tokenized object streams. The native does NOT
    ;; take raw bytes — tokenization stays in Form (or in scan_run path
    ;; A natives where it's already lowered). Bytes → objects is its
    ;; own concern; objects → match is what this native owns.
    ;;
    ;; Output is the SAME shape apply-object-rule returns:
    ;;
    ;;   ("match" caps-alist rest-stream)  on success
    ;;   ("fail"  reason)                  on miss
    ;;
    ;; where caps-alist contains "objects" → bmf-collection and
    ;; "result" → bmf-object whose kind is the rule name and whose
    ;; value is the recipe produced by the rule's action closure.

    ;; --- what stays in Form ----------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;;   - Rule construction (bmf-rule-spec, bmf-reversible-rule-spec,
    ;;     all grammar authoring in form-stdlib/grammars/).
    ;;   - Action callbacks (user closures that take captures and
    ;;     produce a Recipe; substrate-write side effects need Form
    ;;     scope, not kernel scope).
    ;;   - Inverse / reverse-emitter (round-trip authoring stays
    ;;     above the kernel).
    ;;   - Source attribution (bmf-match-source captures + span shape
    ;;     is preserved; native just builds the same lists the Form
    ;;     path would).
    ;;
    ;; --- what moves to the kernel ----------------------------------
    ;;
    ;;   - The pattern-tree walker itself: tag dispatch, sequence loop,
    ;;     choice fallback, capture binding, the cut/stop semantics.
    ;;   - The literal match (kind/value comparison against object).
    ;;   - The consumed-prefix slice.
    ;;
    ;; The native re-enters Form ONLY to invoke the action closure;
    ;; everything else runs as native Go/Rust/TS data manipulation
    ;; on the same list shapes.

    ;; --- fidelity claim --------------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; For every (rule, object-stream) pair where apply-object-rule
    ;; succeeds, bmf_apply_rule_native returns a match-recipe whose
    ;; NodeIDs are byte-identical under node_eq. The action closure
    ;; is the same Form closure either way; the captures alist has
    ;; the same shape; the bmf-match-source span is the same prefix
    ;; of the same stream; the result bmf-object has the same
    ;; (kind, value, source, inverse) tuple. Traceability survives
    ;; because no rule data is reshaped — the native consumes the
    ;; existing rule format and emits the existing match format.
    ;;
    ;; The POC test in tests/bmf-native-apply-band.fk asserts this
    ;; via node_eq on the two emitted result Recipes side-by-side.

    ;; --- 3-kernel parity story -------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; This breath: Go-only native + Form-side fallback wherever
    ;; bmf_apply_rule_native isn't available. Rust and TS register
    ;; the symbol but panic on call so the divergence is LOUD when
    ;; a Form caller hits the native path on the wrong kernel:
    ;;
    ;;   Rust: panic!("bmf_apply_rule_native: not implemented; use \
    ;;                 engine.fk apply-object-rule fallback")
    ;;   TS:   throw new Error("bmf_apply_rule_native: not implemented; \
    ;;                          use engine.fk apply-object-rule fallback")
    ;;
    ;; Engine.fk's apply-object-rule stays untouched. Callers wanting
    ;; the fast path opt in by name; everything else keeps working
    ;; through the interpreted walker. validate.sh keeps comparing
    ;; sibling outputs — the test for bmf_apply_rule_native is run
    ;; against Go only this breath, mirrored across siblings in the
    ;; next breath after the Go shape proves out.

    ;; --- POC scope (this breath) -----------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; The native handles the simplest rule shape only:
    ;;
    ;;   pattern = ("sequence" ("object" kind1 value1)
    ;;                         ("object" kind2 value2)
    ;;                         ... )
    ;;
    ;; — a flat ordered sequence of object-literal matchers with no
    ;; captures, no choice, no star, no opt, no cut. Empty value
    ;; string ("") means kind-only match. Every other pattern shape
    ;; PANICS with a clear "TODO: shape X not yet supported" message
    ;; so callers can't silently fall off the fast path.
    ;;
    ;; Action closure is invoked exactly the way the Form path does:
    ;; with the captures-collection (an empty bmf-collection in this
    ;; POC scope because there are no named captures yet).

    ;; --- next breaths ----------------------------------------------
    ;;
    ;; 1. Add captures (("capture" name child)) — caps alist build.
    ;; 2. Add choice with cut-aware fallback.
    ;; 3. Add star + opt.
    ;; 4. Mirror to Rust + TS, drop the panic stubs.
    ;; 5. Path D: pre-compile rule patterns into a flat opcode stream
    ;;    interned as a Recipe; native dispatch table walks opcodes
    ;;    instead of re-walking the rule tree per match.
    "bmf-native-runtime-design"))
